Comparison to LangGraph isolation
LangGraph (2026 state from current docs and usage) is a stateful graph orchestration runtime:
Nodes = agents/tools, edges = transitions (including conditional).
Everything shares a single typed State object that flows through the entire graph.
Checkpoints = automatic snapshots of the full graph state at every super-step (thread_id + checkpoint_id). Enables time-travel, replay, resume-after-failure.
Subgraphs = modular isolation for chunks of the workflow (you can compile a subgraph with its own checkpointer or share the parent’s).
Human-in-the-loop = interrupt pauses execution, human edits the checkpoint state, then resume.
Multi-agent = supervisor node + handoffs, or separate subgraphs, but state is still merged/visible via the shared checkpoint store.
No native “zero-contact” lanes. Communication is explicit via edges or shared state. Drift detection is emerging (open issues on behavioral drift across checkpoints and trust in swarm handoffs), but it’s soft/observability-based, not hard constitutional lattice + 6-type classification + stop-the-line.
